1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:22,000
This is Emilye Crosby on December 3rd, 2015 with Mrs. Leesco Guster in her home in Port Gibson, Mississippi.

3
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:32,000
We are here with the Civil Rights History Project, which is co-sponsored by the Library of Congress in the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

4
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:36,000
Also here are John Bishop and Guha Shankar.

5
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:43,000
Thank you very much, Mrs. Leesco Guster, for joining us for letting us come to interview you today.

6
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:48,000
Could you start by telling us when and where you were born?

7
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:53,000
Port Gibson, Mississippi.

8
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:59,000
In fact, straight down on, they call it Main Street.

9
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:06,000
I think the little house, it might be gone now, but I was born right across from the Health Department.

10
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:08,000
That's a good location.

11
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:10,000
That's all I can say.

12
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:14,000
Down the whole across from the Health Department.

13
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:17,000
Did your mother have a midwife?

14
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:20,000
Yeah, midwife.

15
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:21,000
What was your born?

16
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:24,000
March 26, 1936.

17
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:28,000
What was your tell us about your family and growing up?

18
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:39,000
Well, mostly I had a single mom at the age of about six.

19
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:42,000
She left and went to Vicksburg, Mississippi.

20
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:45,000
So later she got me.

21
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:47,000
That's why we lived in Vicksburg, Mississippi.

22
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:50,000
She and my father separated.

23
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:53,000
What kind of work did your mother do?

24
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:54,000
Pardon me?

25
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:56,000
What kind of work did your mother do?

26
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,000
Domestic work.

27
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:02,000
And what was your schooling like?

28
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:05,000
What were the schools like you went to?

29
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:09,000
Well, sort of like these.

30
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:14,000
You started one, you go so far like at Magnolia.

31
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:17,000
In Vicksburg, Mississippi, I went to the fifth grade.

32
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:20,000
Then I had to go over to Mac and Ty and go to the eighth.

33
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:24,000
Then you had to go back to Mac know you to go to the tenth.

34
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:25,000
Really?

35
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:26,000
Why didn't you go back?

36
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:28,000
I mean, how did they just...

37
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:31,000
That's how the grades were running.

38
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:33,000
At those schools during that time.

39
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Did you like school?

40
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:36,000
I liked it.

41
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:37,000
Yeah.

42
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:41,000
Did you have a favorite subject?

43
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:43,000
I was kind of lazy.

44
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:45,000
I like home hit.

45
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:49,000
I never did any of the kind of sports.

46
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:50,000
Yeah.

47
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:54,000
What was poor Gibson like in those days?

48
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:59,000
Well, I didn't come here to live until 1953.

49
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Okay.

50
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:01,000
I came now here.

51
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:04,000
So since you were living in Vicksburg, Mississippi when you came to poor Gibson,

52
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:07,000
did it seem like a little small town to you?

53
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:10,000
Well, it wasn't too often that I came now here.

54
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:12,000
But I thought it was...

55
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:14,000
At that time it was fine.

56
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:18,000
But now it's kind of, you know, on the dead side.

57
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:21,000
But at that time I thought it was blooming.

58
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:24,000
Can you describe what it was like in those days?

59
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:26,000
In poor Gibson?

60
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Well, number one, they call it...

61
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:35,000
Back then they called it Negro Street.

62
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:38,000
Joints were all up and down the street.

63
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:40,000
People standing around,

64
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:42,000
stalled up and down the street.

65
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:45,000
But all of that left.

66
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:47,000
That's fair street, right?

67
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:49,000
That's fair street.

68
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:50,000
It was a busy...

69
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:51,000
It was busy.

70
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:54,000
You could hop from one dough to the next one.

71
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:56,000
Did you like going over there?

72
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:58,000
Yeah, I was young at that time.

73
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:00,000
I was young.

74
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:04,000
You were saying at that time...

75
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:05,000
That street...

76
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:07,000
The people were alive.

77
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:10,000
You drink what you want.

78
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:12,000
I wasn't a big drinker.

79
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,000
But I sure liked to eat.

80
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,000
And then you go eat?

81
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:18,000
Where would you eat on a fair street?

82
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:24,000
We each had one cafe called Peaches.

83
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:26,000
She had good food.

84
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:27,000
Yeah.

85
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:28,000
She had good food.

86
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Lara Kelly, young.

87
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:32,000
Yeah.

88
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:37,000
What's your first memory of being aware of race?

89
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:42,000
And segregation?

90
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:47,000
Well, really and truly...

91
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:56,000
I guess all along just by, you know, instinct.

92
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:59,000
But see, at that time it didn't bother me.

93
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Yeah.

94
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:06,000
I just had to do domestic work and stuff like that.

95
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:13,000
But as I grew older and stuff, I just...

96
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:18,000
I've just felt like we need to change.

97
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:27,000
Such as colored bar from colored desk, colored fountain...

98
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:29,000
And white fountain.

99
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:32,000
And I don't think that she would be in.

100
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:35,000
I don't think she would be in.

101
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:37,000
But man, you...

102
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:42,000
I got along with him.

103
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,000
I did.

104
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:49,000
In fact, I lived in Scofield, North.

105
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:52,000
I lived with this since then.

106
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:56,000
But I stayed in the house, not the basement.

107
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:58,000
Which white people?

108
00:05:58,000 --> 00:05:59,000
You were working for them?

109
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:00,000
I was.

110
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:01,000
Yeah.

111
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:03,000
And when did...

112
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:06,000
You went to Chicago in the 50s?

113
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:09,000
50...

114
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:16,000
Of course I came back here around 50 years old.

115
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:19,000
How did Chicago compare to Mississippi?

116
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:20,000
It didn't.

117
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:22,000
You worked yourself to death.

118
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:23,000
Yeah.

119
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:26,000
You get up at night.

120
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:30,000
I had to hop air from the air to the bus trying to get...

121
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:33,000
Get from place to place.

122
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:38,000
And when you leave this dog, when you come back, it's still dog.

123
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:41,000
So you had a time for nothing too much.

124
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:46,000
Because even on Sundays, they would pay something like extra.

125
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:50,000
And if I had a chance to work on Sunday, I worked.

126
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:53,000
That was at Montgomery Ward.

127
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:56,000
So when you first went, you worked for a family?

128
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:00,000
I lived on premises, Scofield and all.

129
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:03,000
And then you went to work for Montgomery Ward?

130
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:06,000
Well, a month, I didn't work.

131
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:09,000
Maybe two months, because I got sick.

132
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:12,000
Because I liked the job.

133
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:15,000
But my nerve got on edge and I didn't know who was happening with me.

134
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:17,000
But I had to stop working.

135
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:21,000
And that's when I started going, really, day work.

136
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:24,000
Now, that's where you work.

137
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:27,000
You do a week's work.

138
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:32,000
Everything, be waiting on you when you get there.

139
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:35,000
The nice one would have some knee pads.

140
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:37,000
But you want to know something?

141
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:43,000
I started cleaning floors on my hand, especially a tile.

142
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:46,000
My self, right here in Port Gibson, nobody told me.

143
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:47,000
Did they really?

144
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:49,000
I did it myself.

145
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:55,000
You told me you started your first job pretty young here.

146
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:57,000
I did.

147
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Did you like working?

148
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:01,000
Did you burn?

149
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:03,000
No, I was about 16.

150
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:05,000
Yeah.

151
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:06,000
I see.

152
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:09,000
In fact, I had a house, I had my own house at 16.

153
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:10,000
Did you really?

154
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:12,000
She was getting my social security check.

155
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:15,600
She'd bring that to me when it come.

156
00:08:15,600 --> 00:08:20,840
And Mrs. Bear.

157
00:08:20,840 --> 00:08:24,080
She was the one who furnished the house for me.

158
00:08:24,080 --> 00:08:26,920
She was the one who bought me clothes and stuff,

159
00:08:26,920 --> 00:08:28,600
so I had no problem.

160
00:08:28,600 --> 00:08:30,920
When you said Ms. Bear, she was the mayor's wife.

161
00:08:30,920 --> 00:08:31,920
Uh-huh.

162
00:08:31,920 --> 00:08:33,680
And you made a reference to she.

163
00:08:33,680 --> 00:08:35,360
You talked about your sister, right?

164
00:08:35,360 --> 00:08:36,520
When you say she would bring you

165
00:08:36,520 --> 00:08:38,400
your social security check.

166
00:08:38,400 --> 00:08:40,200
That's who's getting my check, my sister.

167
00:08:40,200 --> 00:08:40,760
Your sister?

168
00:08:40,760 --> 00:08:41,520
Yeah.

169
00:08:41,520 --> 00:08:42,480
Lindsay Roof.

170
00:08:42,480 --> 00:08:45,080
You've always been Lindsay Roof.

171
00:08:45,080 --> 00:08:46,680
That's her name.

172
00:08:46,680 --> 00:08:48,400
You've always been independent.

173
00:08:48,400 --> 00:08:49,320
I have.

174
00:08:49,320 --> 00:08:51,400
Yeah, I have.

175
00:08:51,400 --> 00:08:53,600
So were you happy to move back to Port Gibson?

176
00:08:53,600 --> 00:08:54,640
I was.

177
00:08:54,640 --> 00:08:58,960
But I guess I might would have still been there.

178
00:08:58,960 --> 00:09:02,800
When I left, I left for a reason.

179
00:09:02,800 --> 00:09:03,920
I was leaving.

180
00:09:03,920 --> 00:09:07,600
The person that I came back and married.

181
00:09:07,600 --> 00:09:09,720
You couldn't get away from him.

182
00:09:09,720 --> 00:09:11,000
I didn't come right away.

183
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:12,640
I gave him a year to think about it.

184
00:09:12,640 --> 00:09:19,400
And tell me about your husband who you married.

185
00:09:19,400 --> 00:09:23,360
Well, he was something like 24 years older than I was.

186
00:09:23,360 --> 00:09:28,320
And he was handsomain, you know, nothing short about him.

187
00:09:28,320 --> 00:09:33,640
And he was the head contractor in the Lumber, you know,

188
00:09:33,640 --> 00:09:38,000
field here in Claiborne County,

189
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:41,240
and vice-president everybody knew Harry.

190
00:09:41,240 --> 00:09:43,480
He was contractor.

191
00:09:43,480 --> 00:09:45,640
So when you came back and you married,

192
00:09:45,640 --> 00:09:47,520
Mr. Harry Guster, did you all stay?

193
00:09:47,520 --> 00:09:49,680
Was this your house then?

194
00:09:49,680 --> 00:09:50,960
It was.

195
00:09:50,960 --> 00:09:54,600
He had the house when I came, you know?

196
00:09:54,600 --> 00:09:55,840
Did he build it?

197
00:09:55,840 --> 00:09:58,400
No, no.

198
00:09:58,400 --> 00:10:01,720
It really wasn't a house when I came.

199
00:10:01,720 --> 00:10:04,040
It was a sec.

200
00:10:04,040 --> 00:10:08,720
He paid something like $2,500 for it.

201
00:10:08,720 --> 00:10:15,880
And when I came, you just, you wouldn't believe.

202
00:10:15,880 --> 00:10:18,360
You could stand on the front and look up under the house

203
00:10:18,360 --> 00:10:19,920
all the way back.

204
00:10:19,920 --> 00:10:24,360
OK, this hall goes straight on back.

205
00:10:24,360 --> 00:10:28,240
What an old bathroom inside.

206
00:10:28,240 --> 00:10:30,080
He stuck it where he could, because it

207
00:10:30,080 --> 00:10:33,120
was having no money or anything at that time.

208
00:10:33,120 --> 00:10:38,280
We had to put it close to where the pipes went stuff were.

209
00:10:38,280 --> 00:10:40,880
So I would never have thought that.

210
00:10:40,880 --> 00:10:44,640
And it didn't get like this when he was living now.

211
00:10:44,640 --> 00:10:48,120
It's been since he had been dead that I did a whole lot of work.

212
00:10:48,120 --> 00:10:52,600
It's kind of ironic since he was a builder, right?

213
00:10:52,600 --> 00:10:55,520
The only thing about it, he did some,

214
00:10:55,520 --> 00:11:00,720
but the whole house, it was just one of the house, you know?

215
00:11:00,720 --> 00:11:03,400
But the lumber and things still good and whatnot.

216
00:11:03,400 --> 00:11:08,840
And he did what he could with the finance he had.

217
00:11:08,840 --> 00:11:12,480
And so I think we were just looking at your birth certificate.

218
00:11:12,480 --> 00:11:13,400
You got married.

219
00:11:13,400 --> 00:11:14,400
I'm not birth certificate.

220
00:11:14,400 --> 00:11:15,400
Marriage.

221
00:11:15,400 --> 00:11:17,600
You got married in like 1959.

222
00:11:17,600 --> 00:11:18,600
Yes, and then.

223
00:11:18,600 --> 00:11:22,760
And when you came back here and married Mr. Gustav,

224
00:11:22,760 --> 00:11:24,160
were you working then?

225
00:11:24,160 --> 00:11:26,000
I'm done with what?

226
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:30,040
I came back here on a three-week vacation.

227
00:11:30,040 --> 00:11:36,440
And I told him that I would, you know, he know what he had done, you know?

228
00:11:36,440 --> 00:11:38,680
Told me he was already married and wasn't married.

229
00:11:38,680 --> 00:11:42,600
I was 19 when I left here.

230
00:11:42,600 --> 00:11:47,400
And I told him I wouldn't come back here unless he married me.

231
00:11:47,400 --> 00:11:56,440
And if he didn't marry me, you know, I was going back within that three weeks.

232
00:11:56,440 --> 00:11:59,960
I was going back because my job was waiting on me.

233
00:11:59,960 --> 00:12:04,600
And he had told me he had put in for the divorce.

234
00:12:04,600 --> 00:12:05,600
And done everything.

235
00:12:05,600 --> 00:12:07,520
He had gone and talked to a lawyer.

236
00:12:07,520 --> 00:12:09,240
He hadn't paid nothing.

237
00:12:09,240 --> 00:12:14,480
And I told him I was going back to Chicago.

238
00:12:14,480 --> 00:12:26,000
I hate that I did it in a lot of instances because that he had a son and that calls friction.

239
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:30,000
And he was, you know, under age time.

240
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:40,920
So his ex-wife, you know, was so sure that he was going to take him back like he did

241
00:12:40,920 --> 00:12:43,320
before when he was, they wouldn't marry that time.

242
00:12:43,320 --> 00:12:47,000
They didn't marry until I went to Chicago.

243
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:48,800
But he didn't do it.

244
00:12:48,800 --> 00:12:52,760
So I had a problem with the child.

245
00:12:52,760 --> 00:12:54,440
Did you stay with you all?

246
00:12:54,440 --> 00:12:55,440
A lot.

247
00:12:55,440 --> 00:12:58,280
That must have been a challenge.

248
00:12:58,280 --> 00:13:06,000
It was a big, big, big change, especially when the mother, you know, put the child up.

249
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:09,240
Two things.

250
00:13:09,240 --> 00:13:15,320
But anyway, he got busy when I told him I was going back and I bet you he went to see

251
00:13:15,320 --> 00:13:19,520
a lawyer then.

252
00:13:19,520 --> 00:13:21,320
He didn't have to convince you to stay.

253
00:13:21,320 --> 00:13:22,320
He did.

254
00:13:22,320 --> 00:13:23,320
Yeah.

255
00:13:23,320 --> 00:13:29,280
And he was always, you know, fair with me about his child too.

256
00:13:29,280 --> 00:13:31,440
You know, he saw what was going on.

257
00:13:31,440 --> 00:13:35,400
He didn't know about his (child) support, but (he sent) me to her every month.

258
00:13:35,400 --> 00:13:37,160
Did you really?

259
00:13:37,160 --> 00:13:38,160
Yeah.

260
00:13:38,160 --> 00:13:44,360
Could the courts require that back then or did you just do it because you thought it was

261
00:13:44,360 --> 00:13:45,360
right?

262
00:13:45,360 --> 00:13:47,360
Oh, hallelujah.

263
00:13:47,360 --> 00:13:48,360
Yeah.

264
00:13:48,360 --> 00:13:54,360
You know, way back down to $25 was a lot of money.

265
00:13:54,360 --> 00:13:56,120
That was a lot of money.

266
00:13:56,120 --> 00:14:00,440
And he couldn't guarantee no work in the one-a-tab.

267
00:14:00,440 --> 00:14:04,240
And it wasn't anywhere in a decree where he didn't have to pay.

268
00:14:04,240 --> 00:14:06,880
If he wasn't working, he ever heard of such.

269
00:14:06,880 --> 00:14:13,760
He still, we were barring money to pay even for my sick mama, you know, everything.

270
00:14:13,760 --> 00:14:21,040
And finally, we had to pay our lawyer to change it around where he didn't have to pay.

271
00:14:21,040 --> 00:14:23,040
If he wasn't working.

272
00:14:23,040 --> 00:14:28,320
So he changed after $25 a month.

273
00:14:28,320 --> 00:14:32,320
I told him, I'm not going to be around here while you're fighting a lawsuit.

274
00:14:32,320 --> 00:14:33,480
I said, you better do it.

275
00:14:33,480 --> 00:14:35,480
I was just pushing him on.

276
00:14:36,480 --> 00:14:38,480
He said, all you came back for $30.

277
00:14:44,480 --> 00:14:49,480
I said the same thing I pushed him and he beat it.

278
00:14:49,480 --> 00:14:55,480
Then the next time, $30,000 in advance,

279
00:14:56,480 --> 00:15:03,480
when she took their (s)on over to Jackson to his brother's house,

280
00:15:03,480 --> 00:15:07,480
left him and went on to Cleveland, Ohio.

281
00:15:07,480 --> 00:15:09,480
But that $30.

282
00:15:09,480 --> 00:15:14,480
But asked me this, she didn't get to next $30.

283
00:15:14,480 --> 00:15:16,480
That was it.

284
00:15:16,480 --> 00:15:18,480
She wasn't taking care of his son.

285
00:15:18,480 --> 00:15:20,480
That's right.

286
00:15:20,480 --> 00:15:22,480
That's right.

287
00:15:23,480 --> 00:15:26,480
You told me at one point that you worked for Mr. Walk-Cut?

288
00:15:26,480 --> 00:15:27,480
Oh, yes.

289
00:15:27,480 --> 00:15:30,480
Can you tell us about, I've been a lot of people don't know about Rabbit Foot Minstrels.

290
00:15:30,480 --> 00:15:31,480
Can you tell us about that?

291
00:15:31,480 --> 00:15:33,480
I can tell you anything about Rabbit Foot Minstrels.

292
00:15:33,480 --> 00:15:39,480
Her or you used to work around Mr. Walk-Cut and also drive him around.

293
00:15:39,480 --> 00:15:41,480
That's how I got acquainted.

294
00:15:41,480 --> 00:15:43,480
He wouldn't let me work.

295
00:15:43,480 --> 00:15:49,480
But he let me work for Hillary when she moved here from Adena, Ohio.

296
00:15:49,480 --> 00:15:51,480
What was her name?

297
00:15:51,480 --> 00:15:52,480
Hillary?

298
00:15:52,480 --> 00:15:53,480
Hillary?

299
00:15:53,480 --> 00:15:54,480
Okay.

300
00:15:54,480 --> 00:15:58,480
And so because of his relationship with Mr. Walk-Cut, he let me work.

301
00:15:58,480 --> 00:16:00,480
And she was his sister?

302
00:16:00,480 --> 00:16:01,480
Oh, his daughter.

303
00:16:01,480 --> 00:16:02,480
His daughter?

304
00:16:02,480 --> 00:16:03,480
Oh, I forgot that.

305
00:16:03,480 --> 00:16:04,480
Her daughter.

306
00:16:04,480 --> 00:16:05,480
Yeah.

307
00:16:05,480 --> 00:16:07,480
And you were doing domestic work at her house.

308
00:16:07,480 --> 00:16:09,480
Did you all get along well?

309
00:16:09,480 --> 00:16:16,480
Very, very much so until her friends got to her house.

310
00:16:16,480 --> 00:16:18,480
She was driving my car.

311
00:16:18,480 --> 00:16:22,480
I had a 1965 and been a long time.

312
00:16:22,480 --> 00:16:28,480
A Catalina stopped making a Catalina Pontiac.

313
00:16:28,480 --> 00:16:31,480
And I had a key to the house.

314
00:16:31,480 --> 00:16:36,480
Now, my new app was not even a member of the NAACP.

315
00:16:36,480 --> 00:16:40,480
My thing was, I wanted to vote.

316
00:16:40,480 --> 00:16:44,480
I wanted to get people registered to vote.

317
00:16:44,480 --> 00:16:48,480
I wanted a little recognition and a better job.

318
00:16:48,480 --> 00:16:53,480
I may not get it, but somebody else come along.

319
00:16:53,480 --> 00:16:59,480
So every evening, when I get off, I would go up there

320
00:16:59,480 --> 00:17:03,480
about what's their drugstore name, McFatter's.

321
00:17:03,480 --> 00:17:07,480
That's where Rudy Shields and all of them hung out.

322
00:17:07,480 --> 00:17:10,480
And because I wasn't even going to the meetings.

323
00:17:10,480 --> 00:17:12,480
But I got acquainted with Rudy.

324
00:17:12,480 --> 00:17:16,480
And I grew all over the Claiborne County in canvassing.

325
00:17:16,480 --> 00:17:24,480
You know, after the federal, people came in to vote.

326
00:17:24,480 --> 00:17:27,480
And the people would see me standing out there.

327
00:17:27,480 --> 00:17:29,480
So they got to her.

328
00:17:29,480 --> 00:17:32,480
It wasn't like, when I was no secret, I had done my work

329
00:17:32,480 --> 00:17:34,480
at the house and everything.

330
00:17:34,480 --> 00:17:39,480
So I don't think you can take your job home with you.

331
00:17:39,480 --> 00:17:42,480
One more now. I was there.

332
00:17:42,480 --> 00:17:47,480
I noticed the change before that particular moment.

333
00:17:47,480 --> 00:17:51,480
She didn't know I was there because I didn't drive up that wall.

334
00:17:51,480 --> 00:17:56,480
And she came in with a, saying a few chores words.

335
00:17:56,480 --> 00:18:00,480
I don't even remember who she was talking to.

336
00:18:00,480 --> 00:18:08,480
And whether she was going to, you know, I can't use the term she used.

337
00:18:08,480 --> 00:18:11,480
And then she saw I was there.

338
00:18:11,480 --> 00:18:17,480
She said, well, Lee, we don't need you anymore.

339
00:18:17,480 --> 00:18:18,480
I support Thank you.

340
00:18:18,480 --> 00:18:22,480
And I left walking because I didn't drive up that day.

341
00:18:22,480 --> 00:18:24,480
That was it.

342
00:18:24,480 --> 00:18:31,480
But she came from Ohio and joined in with the people here in Claiborne County.

343
00:18:31,480 --> 00:18:35,480
So she has a different attitude until she's getting with them.

344
00:18:35,480 --> 00:18:37,480
So you're not going to use her words.

345
00:18:37,480 --> 00:18:38,480
But what was she basically saying?

346
00:18:38,480 --> 00:18:43,480
What was her point to her friends?

347
00:18:43,480 --> 00:18:46,480
She was tired of all that damn shit.

348
00:18:46,480 --> 00:18:47,480
That's what she said.

349
00:18:47,480 --> 00:18:49,480
And she's talking about the voting?

350
00:18:49,480 --> 00:18:53,480
She was talking about them coming to her and me.

351
00:18:53,480 --> 00:18:55,480
I never stopped going up there.

352
00:18:55,480 --> 00:18:59,480
You know, every evening I would go up there and we can just bring in people

353
00:18:59,480 --> 00:19:04,480
to, I wore out a set of tires I can tell you.

354
00:19:04,480 --> 00:19:13,480
So you said at first you weren't an NAACP member and you weren't even going to the meeting.

355
00:19:13,480 --> 00:19:15,480
You were a voter register.

356
00:19:15,480 --> 00:19:17,480
Were you aware of it?

357
00:19:17,480 --> 00:19:18,480
Did you know?

358
00:19:18,480 --> 00:19:20,480
I knew about the meetings and stuff.

359
00:19:20,480 --> 00:19:21,480
I knew all about that.

360
00:19:21,480 --> 00:19:28,480
But like I said, I was interested in getting people to register and vote because that vote and that dollar was what matter.

361
00:19:28,480 --> 00:19:29,480
As far as I'm concerned.

362
00:19:29,480 --> 00:19:32,480
And that's what I was about.

363
00:19:32,480 --> 00:19:35,480
And I wasn't about no all white.

364
00:19:35,480 --> 00:19:38,480
And I wasn't about no all black.

365
00:19:38,480 --> 00:19:40,480
And I...

366
00:19:40,480 --> 00:19:43,480
When she came up there talking to you.

367
00:19:43,480 --> 00:19:45,480
She didn't tell me.

368
00:19:45,480 --> 00:19:46,480
She was talking to me.

369
00:19:46,480 --> 00:19:48,480
I don't even remember who it was.

370
00:19:48,480 --> 00:19:50,480
So if she was, I don't know.

371
00:19:50,480 --> 00:19:52,480
But I heard her.

372
00:19:52,480 --> 00:19:56,480
So I said, well I didn't get it.

373
00:19:56,480 --> 00:19:59,480
I didn't go.

374
00:19:59,480 --> 00:20:02,480
Well, you could tell.

375
00:20:02,480 --> 00:20:05,480
It was fired up.

376
00:20:05,480 --> 00:20:11,480
When she said she couldn't use you anymore.

377
00:20:11,480 --> 00:20:22,480
Well, she was polite in saying that.

378
00:20:22,480 --> 00:20:29,480
But I heard all she had to say.

379
00:20:29,480 --> 00:20:35,480
So you would go around by Mr. McFatter's and that's where the federal administration was.

380
00:20:35,480 --> 00:20:38,480
They were upstairs with Dr. Barnes.

381
00:20:38,480 --> 00:20:39,480
Okay.

382
00:20:39,480 --> 00:20:42,480
And how did you meet Rudy Shields?

383
00:20:42,480 --> 00:20:45,480
On the street in front of the drug stop.

384
00:20:45,480 --> 00:20:47,480
Did he start talking to you?

385
00:20:47,480 --> 00:20:50,480
Tell us what he was like.

386
00:20:50,480 --> 00:20:53,480
Brave.

387
00:20:53,480 --> 00:20:57,480
Wasn't scared of nothing.

388
00:20:57,480 --> 00:21:05,480
I don't know how to explain Rudy except he...

389
00:21:05,480 --> 00:21:07,480
He just...

390
00:21:07,480 --> 00:21:09,480
He wasn't radical.

391
00:21:09,480 --> 00:21:13,480
But he just spoke up of what the things that he knew.

392
00:21:13,480 --> 00:21:15,480
You know.

393
00:21:15,480 --> 00:21:18,480
And...

394
00:21:19,480 --> 00:21:21,480
He was doing what I wanted to do.

395
00:21:21,480 --> 00:21:23,480
I tried to get people register.

396
00:21:23,480 --> 00:21:27,480
So I volunteered my car.

397
00:21:27,480 --> 00:21:29,480
And my hood was going to...

398
00:21:29,480 --> 00:21:30,480
45.

399
00:21:30,480 --> 00:21:33,480
That was a suit.

400
00:21:33,480 --> 00:21:35,480
My gun or something.

401
00:21:35,480 --> 00:21:37,480
It would leave me shoot.

402
00:21:37,480 --> 00:21:38,480
It skipped.

403
00:21:38,480 --> 00:21:40,480
I didn't know that.

404
00:21:40,480 --> 00:21:42,480
You're reliant on it.

405
00:21:42,480 --> 00:21:45,480
He was reliant on it.

406
00:21:45,480 --> 00:21:47,480
No, Rudy.

407
00:21:47,480 --> 00:21:49,480
He was living.

408
00:21:49,480 --> 00:21:51,480
But I didn't let him go out there.

409
00:21:51,480 --> 00:21:53,480
See, he was sickly.

410
00:21:53,480 --> 00:21:56,480
And I didn't let him march or anything.

411
00:21:56,480 --> 00:21:58,480
Because, you know, if he had gone to jail,

412
00:21:58,480 --> 00:22:01,480
then that wouldn't have been good or far.

413
00:22:01,480 --> 00:22:03,480
Did he want to be involved, didn't he?

414
00:22:03,480 --> 00:22:04,480
He was interested.

415
00:22:04,480 --> 00:22:05,480
He wanted to be involved.

416
00:22:05,480 --> 00:22:06,480
Oh, he was involved.

417
00:22:06,480 --> 00:22:07,480
Yeah.

418
00:22:07,480 --> 00:22:10,480
He went to all the meetings.

419
00:22:10,480 --> 00:22:13,480
The people stayed here in the house.

420
00:22:13,480 --> 00:22:16,480
He slept back there and I slept up here.

421
00:22:16,480 --> 00:22:19,480
And I was shot gone.

422
00:22:19,480 --> 00:22:21,480
Staying up, making sure.

423
00:22:21,480 --> 00:22:24,480
Yeah, it wasn't comfortable at all.

424
00:22:24,480 --> 00:22:27,480
Looking back, I wouldn't do it again.

425
00:22:27,480 --> 00:22:29,480
No, you wouldn't.

426
00:22:29,480 --> 00:22:31,480
I wouldn't do it.

427
00:22:31,480 --> 00:22:33,480
Number one, I'm old.

428
00:22:33,480 --> 00:22:35,480
And I don't have a husband.

429
00:22:35,480 --> 00:22:37,480
I wouldn't take it on.

430
00:22:37,480 --> 00:22:41,480
Then, you don't have anybody to back you up now.

431
00:22:41,480 --> 00:22:44,480
Like in a legal way, you get in jail.

432
00:22:44,480 --> 00:22:46,480
You could be sure you're going to get out.

433
00:22:46,480 --> 00:22:49,480
Because, you know, they won't have a lawyer's thing.

434
00:22:49,480 --> 00:22:53,480
And the people who come up to go, but nobody's going to trust

435
00:22:53,480 --> 00:22:55,480
putting their property and stuff up.

436
00:22:55,480 --> 00:22:57,480
Well, for what?

437
00:22:57,480 --> 00:22:59,480
Maybe I better not say this.

438
00:22:59,480 --> 00:23:03,480
But, you know, we don't have anything about it to back us here

439
00:23:03,480 --> 00:23:06,480
in Claiborne County, believe me.

440
00:23:06,480 --> 00:23:10,480
But at the time, did you hesitate?

441
00:23:10,480 --> 00:23:13,480
Did you have any hesitation back in the 16th?

442
00:23:13,480 --> 00:23:15,480
About standing here.

443
00:23:15,480 --> 00:23:18,480
About them staying here, about doing voter registration.

444
00:23:18,480 --> 00:23:19,480
No.

445
00:23:19,480 --> 00:23:21,480
No, no, no, no.

446
00:23:21,480 --> 00:23:25,480
I don't know where it came from, but I was brave.

447
00:23:25,480 --> 00:23:27,480
Yeah.

448
00:23:27,480 --> 00:23:28,480
What about Mr. Harry Guster?

449
00:23:28,480 --> 00:23:31,480
Was he working when you were doing the movement?

450
00:23:31,480 --> 00:23:34,480
Well, for why?

451
00:23:34,480 --> 00:23:35,480
How then?

452
00:23:35,480 --> 00:23:41,480
He was being spurred, Louisiana, and put you in some of those

453
00:23:41,480 --> 00:23:46,480
of the places, mostly, where he worked with nobody.

454
00:23:46,480 --> 00:23:51,480
We lived out of the A-check, $114 a month.

455
00:23:51,480 --> 00:23:53,480
Back there was a lot of money.

456
00:23:53,480 --> 00:23:56,480
I was a little hundered, had to go to the bank on the car.

457
00:23:56,480 --> 00:24:03,480
And $43-and-cents.

458
00:24:03,480 --> 00:24:06,480
So security check, because he really hadn't paid into it.

459
00:24:06,480 --> 00:24:10,480
You know, he paid for his workers, but he hadn't paid it and

460
00:24:10,480 --> 00:24:13,480
he was paying into it too much.

461
00:24:13,480 --> 00:24:17,480
So he lost all his work, I lost all my work.

462
00:24:17,480 --> 00:24:22,480
The $20 a week work, but I was getting from Hill Wall car.

463
00:24:22,480 --> 00:24:24,480
Was that a hardship for you all?

464
00:24:24,480 --> 00:24:26,480
Was it a hardship?

465
00:24:26,480 --> 00:24:30,480
Back then, you know, you could take a little nut and make it.

466
00:24:30,480 --> 00:24:33,480
If you know how to do it.

467
00:24:33,480 --> 00:24:35,480
You could do it.

468
00:24:35,480 --> 00:24:38,480
Well, tell us, good money.

469
00:24:38,480 --> 00:24:43,480
I know he came into the area with Charles Evers.

470
00:24:43,480 --> 00:24:44,480
He did.

471
00:24:44,480 --> 00:24:45,480
From Chicago.

472
00:24:45,480 --> 00:24:48,480
Did he talk about Chicago at home or why he came?

473
00:24:48,480 --> 00:24:51,480
He didn't have time to talk about nothing.

474
00:24:51,480 --> 00:24:57,480
But whether he came here to do, he didn't have conversations.

475
00:24:57,480 --> 00:25:01,480
Now, he stayed here, but long enough to sleep.

476
00:25:01,480 --> 00:25:03,480
And that's about it.

477
00:25:03,480 --> 00:25:05,480
What would he say about why he was, you know,

478
00:25:05,480 --> 00:25:10,480
what he wanted to do here when he was trying to accomplish?

479
00:25:10,480 --> 00:25:15,480
What he said was said at, you know, different meetings and things.

480
00:25:15,480 --> 00:25:18,480
It wouldn't be a personal thing.

481
00:25:18,480 --> 00:25:20,480
Was he quiet?

482
00:25:20,480 --> 00:25:22,480
Like I said, he slept here.

483
00:25:22,480 --> 00:25:24,480
I feed him, you know, in the morning.

484
00:25:24,480 --> 00:25:29,480
I wouldn't send him over tonight that he eats somewhere else, you know.

485
00:25:29,480 --> 00:25:32,480
So when you and Rudy would go out,

486
00:25:32,480 --> 00:25:35,480
and listen for a voter registration,

487
00:25:35,480 --> 00:25:37,480
tell us what that was like.

488
00:25:37,480 --> 00:25:41,480
Well, we had people, you know,

489
00:25:41,480 --> 00:25:45,480
over the people and things who didn't understand.

490
00:25:45,480 --> 00:25:48,480
They wouldn't worry about voting or anything,

491
00:25:48,480 --> 00:25:51,480
because we had never done it before.

492
00:25:51,480 --> 00:25:53,480
We had never done it.

493
00:25:53,480 --> 00:25:59,480
And some would go with us, and some wouldn't, you know.

494
00:25:59,480 --> 00:26:01,480
But we, that didn't stop.

495
00:26:01,480 --> 00:26:04,480
We go keep on, you know, going.

496
00:26:04,480 --> 00:26:08,480
Was it, did you try to convince people?

497
00:26:08,480 --> 00:26:11,480
Well, yeah.

498
00:26:11,480 --> 00:26:13,480
We tried.

499
00:26:13,480 --> 00:26:18,480
But mostly the people who live on plantations, they were afraid.

500
00:26:18,480 --> 00:26:19,480
They were free.

501
00:26:19,480 --> 00:26:22,480
Does he need one?

502
00:26:22,480 --> 00:26:24,480
What's that?

503
00:26:24,480 --> 00:26:27,480
Oh, okay.

504
00:26:28,480 --> 00:26:30,480
Okay, we're back.

505
00:26:30,480 --> 00:26:34,480
Did you ever run into any trouble or any problems when you were registering people?

506
00:26:34,480 --> 00:26:35,480
Oh, yeah.

507
00:26:35,480 --> 00:26:36,480
Rocky Springs.

508
00:26:36,480 --> 00:26:37,480
I know we'll forget that.

509
00:26:37,480 --> 00:26:39,480
We went out there.

510
00:26:39,480 --> 00:26:43,480
It was two trails, right together.

511
00:26:43,480 --> 00:26:45,480
Now, I'm telling the story.

512
00:26:45,480 --> 00:26:46,480
It was one trail.

513
00:26:46,480 --> 00:26:48,480
It was kind of long.

514
00:26:48,480 --> 00:26:54,480
And they told us to come back the next day.

515
00:26:54,480 --> 00:26:59,480
Well, when we got back, the owner of the property was,

516
00:26:59,480 --> 00:27:04,480
and a pickup truck was parked up on the hill.

517
00:27:04,480 --> 00:27:07,480
And he had his shot go.

518
00:27:07,480 --> 00:27:10,480
You know, how they have it across the back of the truck.

519
00:27:10,480 --> 00:27:13,480
And I told him, I call him Mr. Shields.

520
00:27:13,480 --> 00:27:14,480
I said, Mr. Shields.

521
00:27:14,480 --> 00:27:16,480
I said, he got it going.

522
00:27:16,480 --> 00:27:17,480
He said, that's all right.

523
00:27:17,480 --> 00:27:18,480
Mr. Harry Guster.

524
00:27:18,480 --> 00:27:20,480
That's what he called Mr. Harry Guster.

525
00:27:20,480 --> 00:27:23,480
He said, we're not doing anything wrong.

526
00:27:23,480 --> 00:27:30,480
So, the man got out of his truck and came over where the people were standing.

527
00:27:30,480 --> 00:27:33,480
We don't want to lose what us got.

