01:09:59,360 --> 01:10:01,360
They look here, it's still there.

1287
01:10:01,360 --> 01:10:03,360
Don't look like me.

1288
01:10:03,360 --> 01:10:05,360
I saw him when they were painting it.

1289
01:10:05,360 --> 01:10:09,360
You know, look like me.

1290
01:10:09,360 --> 01:10:13,360
Did you ever think there would be a civil rights mural in poor Gibson?

1291
01:10:13,360 --> 01:10:15,360
No. Let me tell you.

1292
01:10:15,360 --> 01:10:19,360
When, um, car, where, that was for something else.

1293
01:10:19,360 --> 01:10:26,360
But he had us meeting, talking about, uh, a museum and all of this kind of stuff.

1294
01:10:26,360 --> 01:10:28,360
And he even got money.

1295
01:10:28,360 --> 01:10:31,360
You know, churches give him money because I took $100 in my church.

1296
01:10:31,360 --> 01:10:34,360
And come to find out after he didn't go through it,

1297
01:10:34,360 --> 01:10:36,360
he turned it over to the NAACP.

1298
01:10:36,360 --> 01:10:38,360
But you don't do stuff like that.

1299
01:10:38,360 --> 01:10:39,360
No.

1300
01:10:39,360 --> 01:10:41,360
You get it back to where you got it from.

1301
01:10:41,360 --> 01:10:47,360
And, uh, I never thought we'd have a mural.

1302
01:10:47,360 --> 01:10:51,360
But, Kenneth Ross is smart. He's very smart.

1303
01:10:51,360 --> 01:10:52,360
Yeah.

1304
01:10:52,360 --> 01:10:57,360
What about the exhibit over in the county building?

1305
01:10:57,360 --> 01:11:01,360
Well, the exhibit, the civil rights exhibit?

1306
01:11:01,360 --> 01:11:03,360
On inside the courthouse.

1307
01:11:03,360 --> 01:11:04,360
Yeah.

1308
01:11:04,360 --> 01:11:06,360
Well, they'd do it like this.

1309
01:11:06,360 --> 01:11:09,360
They almost sing in and talk.

1310
01:11:09,360 --> 01:11:10,360
Yeah.

1311
01:11:10,360 --> 01:11:14,360
You know the same thing they did at the meeting.

1312
01:11:14,360 --> 01:11:17,360
George Henry, very well deserved.

1313
01:11:17,360 --> 01:11:25,360
Reverend Dawson deserves, you know, those people worked.

1314
01:11:25,360 --> 01:11:29,360
And then she Reverend Dawson went out there when it was hot.

1315
01:11:29,360 --> 01:11:37,360
You know, when you went home, it was, it had cooled down.

1316
01:11:37,360 --> 01:11:42,360
And Miss Bellma told me one time, oh, right, Lynn, I see that.

1317
01:11:42,360 --> 01:11:45,360
I think I mentioned this though.

1318
01:11:45,360 --> 01:11:48,360
Rev. Dawson stepped down.

1319
01:11:48,360 --> 01:11:54,360
And, uh, I said, well, he stepped down because of all the mess that was going on.

1320
01:11:54,360 --> 01:11:57,360
I didn't mean the NAACP was a mess.

1321
01:11:57,360 --> 01:12:00,360
But the mess going on in his church, you know.

1322
01:12:00,360 --> 01:12:06,360
And, and it, you call it, she said, you call it a mess.

1323
01:12:06,360 --> 01:12:08,360
Look what that mess got you.

1324
01:12:08,360 --> 01:12:10,360
I said, I wasn't talking about the NAACP.

1325
01:12:10,360 --> 01:12:15,360
You know, I said, well, didn't give me no job.

1326
01:12:15,360 --> 01:12:16,360
Nothing first.

1327
01:12:16,360 --> 01:12:17,360
And she thought about it.

1328
01:12:17,360 --> 01:12:18,360
It got me a job first.

1329
01:12:18,360 --> 01:12:22,360
Tell me how he had started, which he did not need.

1330
01:12:22,360 --> 01:12:23,360
No.

1331
01:12:23,360 --> 01:12:31,360
So I found those people out to be selfish.

1332
01:12:31,360 --> 01:12:36,360
Now, Carlos was my friend, close friend.

1333
01:12:37,360 --> 01:12:41,360
Margot, we were nowhere around when it was going on.

1334
01:12:41,360 --> 01:12:51,360
Soon as she got in town because of who she was, they appointed her president over our mart.

1335
01:12:51,360 --> 01:12:55,360
You know, why can't, I mean, we were here doing a struggle.

1336
01:12:55,360 --> 01:12:58,360
Why couldn't they get somebody from right here?

1337
01:12:58,360 --> 01:13:04,360
You know, we had some people know something because she didn't know, had to bring the Folsom Jackson.

1338
01:13:04,360 --> 01:13:07,360
She was smirking all of them.

1339
01:13:07,360 --> 01:13:08,360
And I never did.

1340
01:13:08,360 --> 01:13:10,360
It was $25.

1341
01:13:10,360 --> 01:13:11,360
Sure.

1342
01:13:11,360 --> 01:13:15,360
I hate $25, but I didn't buy one.

1343
01:13:15,360 --> 01:13:17,360
I didn't buy one.

1344
01:13:17,360 --> 01:13:20,360
Did you use the shop over at our mart?

1345
01:13:20,360 --> 01:13:22,360
I'd go and then pass my all items.

1346
01:13:22,360 --> 01:13:24,360
But it was so hot.

1347
01:13:24,360 --> 01:13:28,360
People were trying to go where they could get it cheap.

1348
01:13:28,360 --> 01:13:31,360
But I had no bags of this.

1349
01:13:34,360 --> 01:13:39,360
So are you proud of what you did in the morning?

1350
01:13:39,360 --> 01:13:41,360
I'm proud.

1351
01:13:41,360 --> 01:13:44,360
Not am.

1352
01:13:44,360 --> 01:13:46,360
But I didn't do it for no show now.

1353
01:13:46,360 --> 01:13:51,360
I didn't do it for no show.

1354
01:13:51,360 --> 01:13:54,360
I was talking to somebody recently about Rudy Shields.

1355
01:13:54,360 --> 01:13:56,360
I can't remember who it was.

1356
01:13:56,360 --> 01:13:59,360
I was trying to remember.

1357
01:13:59,360 --> 01:14:00,360
Lately?

1358
01:14:00,360 --> 01:14:01,360
Yeah.

1359
01:14:02,360 --> 01:14:04,360
George used to talk about it all the time.

1360
01:14:04,360 --> 01:14:09,360
George thought when Rudy got sick, that I should take him.

1361
01:14:09,360 --> 01:14:11,360
I said, George, I can't do that.

1362
01:14:11,360 --> 01:14:13,360
I said, this was doing the movement.

1363
01:14:13,360 --> 01:14:14,360
I had a husband.

1364
01:14:14,360 --> 01:14:17,360
I said, I can't have nobody to seek a man I'm working to.

1365
01:14:17,360 --> 01:14:18,360
I had a (husband) - speaker self-correction.

1366
01:14:18,360 --> 01:14:20,360
I thought, yeah, well, good friend.

1367
01:14:20,360 --> 01:14:24,360
I said, we were good friends during the (time of) doing the movement.

1368
01:14:24,360 --> 01:14:26,360
But I couldn't go out there for a while.

1369
01:14:26,360 --> 01:14:27,360
I know who it was.

1370
01:14:27,360 --> 01:14:32,360
It was a man in Yazoo that he used to stay with.

1371
01:14:32,360 --> 01:14:33,360
And it's his daughter.

1372
01:14:33,360 --> 01:14:34,360
He's trying to write something.

1373
01:14:34,360 --> 01:14:37,360
She's trying to write something about Rudy Sheerl.

1374
01:14:37,360 --> 01:14:42,360
She was asking me, so that was good.

1375
01:14:42,360 --> 01:14:43,360
We'll discuss it.

1376
01:14:43,360 --> 01:14:47,360
Thank you so much for visiting with us and sharing your story.

1377
01:14:47,360 --> 01:14:49,360
We're very happy to have it.

1378
01:14:49,360 --> 01:14:51,360
And it's the same story.

1379
01:14:51,360 --> 01:14:52,360
The same story.

1380
01:14:52,360 --> 01:14:53,360
The same story.

1381
01:14:53,360 --> 01:14:54,360
The same story.

1382
01:14:55,360 --> 01:14:57,360
I don't know if we have the way to tell it.

1383
01:14:57,360 --> 01:15:00,360
Thanks, Miss Gusted.

1384
01:15:00,360 --> 01:15:08,360
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum

1385
